  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>This is a catch-all for things I noticed (some of which should get fixed) with
the tar mission:

1. (nit) The first sentence "The tar program creates and unpacks archives called
tarballs" should probably be "The tar program creates, unpacks, and manipulates
archives called tarballs".

2. The tar command needs more explanation.  Seems like this page is possibly
telling people about tar who have never used tar before.  I think this could be
fixed with examples of usage.

3. If a user is interested in more information, he/she would need links to more
information.  A link to the wikipedia page would be great.  Links to other tar
documentation would also be great.

4. People learn in different ways, so it might be a good idea to additionally
link to a screencast on tar usage.  I hoped that FOSSCasts
(<a href="http://fosscasts.com/">http://fosscasts.com/</a>) would have an episode on tar, but there isn't one.  It'd
be cool to ping John about creating one or alternatively find someone else who's
good at doing screencasts that are well produced, well scripted, and to the
point to do one.  Asheesh mentioned getting a user-contributed one.  That'd work
as long as it was good.

5. I'd break up the mission paragraphs into bullet points--one for each
requirement.  It's easier to parse and more likely a user will fulfill all the
requirements.

6. What happens if the user doesn't have tar on his/her system?  For example,
Windows doesn't come with tar.  Is it outside the scope of these missions to
explain how to install tar?  This is kind of a big topic, so I'm not sure what
the right answer is.

7. If the user completes the mission and returns to the mission page, there
should be a message at the top of the page saying the user has completed the
mission and telling the user that he/she can do it again if he/she likes (or
something like that).

8. A second part to this mission (or second mission) would be to have the user
download a tarball, extract the files, and upload a README file from the tarball.</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
